1 UNIT-4 IMMUTABLE DATA STRUCTURES

1.0.1 4.1 Strings:

Strings in Python are immutable, meaning their values cannot be changed after creation.

  • Immutability:
    • Strings cannot be modified once created.
my_string = "Hello, World!"
my_string[0] = "hi"
TypeError: 'str' object does not support item assignment
  • Declaring:
    • Syntax: my_string = "Hello, World!"
    • Description: Declares a string with the value âHello, World!â.
my_string = "Hello, World!"
  • Accessing through for loop:

    • Syntax:

      for char in my_string:
    print(char)

    • Description: Accesses each character in the string using a for loop.

for char in my_string:
        print(char, end = "")
Hello, World!
  • Slicing:
    • Syntax: substring = my_string[7:12]
    • Description: Creates a substring from index 7 to 11.
substring = my_string[7:12]
substring
'World'
  • Concatenation:
    • Syntax: new_string = my_string + " How are you?"
    • Description: Concatenates a new string â How are you?â.
new_string = my_string + " How are you?"
new_string
'Hello, World! How are you?'
  • Length (len):
    • Syntax: length = len(my_string)
    • Description: Gets the length of the string.
length = len(my_string)
length
13
  • capitalize():
    • Syntax: capitalized = my_string.capitalize()
    • Description: Returns a capitalized version of the string.
capitalized = my_string.capitalize()
capitalized
'Hello, world!'
  • enumerate():

    • Syntax:

      for index, char in enumerate(my_string):
    print(index, char)

    • Description: Enumerates through the string, printing index and character.

for index, char in enumerate(my_string):
    print(index, char)
0 H
1 e
2 l
3 l
4 o
5 ,
6  
7 W
8 o
9 r
10 l
11 d
12 !
  • isalnum():
    • Syntax: is_alphanumeric = my_string.isalnum()
    • Description: Checks if the string is alphanumeric.
is_alphanumeric = my_string.isalnum()
is_alphanumeric
False
  • isalpha():
    • Syntax: is_alpha = my_string.isalpha()
    • Description: Checks if the string is alphabetic.
is_alpha = my_string.isalpha()
is_alpha
False
  • islower():
    • Syntax: is_lower = my_string.islower()
    • Description: Checks if the string is in lowercase.
is_lower = my_string.islower()
is_lower
False
  • isupper():
    • Syntax: is_upper = my_string.isupper()
    • Description: Checks if the string is in uppercase.
is_upper = my_string.isupper()
is_upper
False
  • lower():
    • Syntax: lower_case = my_string.lower()
    • Description: Converts the string to lowercase.
lower_case = my_string.lower()
lower_case
'hello, world!'
  • upper():
    • Syntax: upper_case = my_string.upper()
    • Description: Converts the string to uppercase.
upper_case = my_string.upper()
upper_case
'HELLO, WORLD!'
  • isnumeric():
    • Syntax: is_numeric = my_string.isnumeric()
    • Description: Checks if the string is numeric.
is_numeric = my_string.isnumeric()
is_numeric
False
  • find():
    • Syntax: index = my_string.find("World")
    • Description: Finds the index of the substring âWorldâ.
    • If the substring is not found, find() returns -1.
index = my_string.find("World")
index
7
  • index():
    • Syntax: index = my_string.index("World")
    • Description: Finds the index of the substring âWorldâ.
    • If the substring is not found, index() raises a ValueError.
index = my_string.index("World")
index
7
  • split():
    • Syntax: words = my_string.split(",")
    • Description: Splits the string into a list of words using a comma as a delimiter.
words = my_string.split(",")
words
['Hello', ' World!']
  • strip():
    • Syntax: stripped = my_string.strip()
    • Description: Removes leading and trailing whitespaces from the string.
stripped = my_string.strip()
stripped
'Hello, World!'
  • Removing punctuation using translate():

    • Syntax:

      import string
translator = str.maketrans("", "", string.punctuation)
no_punctuation = my_string.translate(translator)

    • Description: Removes punctuation from the string.

import string
translator = str.maketrans("", "", string.punctuation)
no_punctuation = my_string.translate(translator)
no_punctuation
'Hello World'
  • count():
    • Syntax: occurrence = my_string.count("l")
    • Description: Counts the occurrences of the character âlâ in the string.
occurrence = my_string.count("l")
occurrence
3

1.1 4.2 Tuples:

Tuples are immutable sequences.

  • Immutability:
    • Tuples cannot be modified once created.
my_tuple = (1, 2, 3)
my_tuple[1] = 9
TypeError: 'tuple' object does not support item assignment
  • Create:
    • Syntax: my_tuple = (1, 2, 3)
    • Description: Creates a tuple with values 1, 2, and 3.
my_tuple = (1,2,3)
  • Assign:
    • Syntax: a, b, c = my_tuple
    • Description: Assigns values from the tuple to variables.
a, b, c = my_tuple
print(a,b,c)
1 2 3
  • Access:
    • Syntax: value = my_tuple[1]
    • Description: Accesses the value at index 1 of the tuple.
value = my_tuple[1]
value
2
  • Delete (del):
    • Syntax: del my_tuple
    • Description: Deletes the tuple.
del my_tuple
  • Slicing:
    • Syntax: subset = my_tuple[1:3]
    • Description: Creates a subset of the tuple from index 1 to 2.
my_tuple = (1,2,3)
subset = my_tuple[1:3]
subset
(2, 3)
  • Concatenation:
    • Syntax: new_tuple = my_tuple + (4, 5)
    • Description: Concatenates a new tuple.
new_tuple = my_tuple + (4, 5)
new_tuple
(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
  • Comparing tuples:
    • Syntax: compare_result = (1, 2, 3) == (1, 2, 3)
    • Description: Compares two tuples for equality.
compare_result = (1, 2, 3) == (1, 2, 3)
compare_result
True
  • Count function:
    • Syntax: occurrences = my_tuple.count(2)
    • Description: Counts the occurrences of the value 2 in the tuple.
occurrences = my_tuple.count(2)
occurrences
1

1.2 4.3 Built-in Functions:

Python provides various built-in functions for common operations.

  • sorted():
    • Syntax: sorted_list = sorted([3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2])
    • Description: Returns a sorted version of the list.
sorted_list = sorted([3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2])
print(sorted_list)
print(type(sorted_list))
[1, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 9]
<class 'list'>
  • reversed():
    • Syntax: reversed_list = list(reversed([3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2]))
    • Description: Returns a reversed version of the list.
reversed_list = list(reversed([3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2]))
reversed_list
[2, 9, 5, 1, 4, 1, 3]
  • min():
    • Syntax: minimum_value = min(3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2)
    • Description: Returns the minimum value from the arguments.
minimum_value = min(3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2)
minimum_value
1
  • max():
    • Syntax: maximum_value = max(3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2)
    • Description: Returns the maximum value from the arguments.
maximum_value = max(3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2)
maximum_value
9
a={1,2,3}
b={1,2,3,4,5}
a>b
False

2 UNIT-5 MUTABLE DATA STRUCTURES

2.1 5.1 Lists:

Lists in Python are mutable, meaning their elements can be modified after creation.

  • Mutability:
    • Lists can be modified after creation.
my_list = [1, 2, 3]
my_list[0] = 100
my_list
[100, 2, 3]
  • Declaring:
    • Syntax: my_list = [1, 2, 3]
    • Description: Declares a list with values 1, 2, and 3.
my_list = [1, 2, 3]
my_list
[1, 2, 3]
  • Accessing through for loop:

    • Syntax:

      for item in my_list:
    print(item)

    • Description: Accesses each element in the list using a for loop.

for item in my_list:
    print(item)
1
2
3
  • append():
    • Syntax: my_list.append(4)
    • Description: Appends the value 4 to the end of the list.
my_list.append(4)
my_list
[1, 2, 3, 4]
  • count():
    • Syntax: count = my_list.count(2)
    • Description: Counts the occurrences of the value 2 in the list.
count = my_list.count(4)
count
1
  • extend():
    • Syntax: my_list.extend([5, 6])
    • Description: Extends the list by adding elements from another list.
my_list.extend([5, 6])
my_list
[1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
  • index():
    • Syntax: index = my_list.index(3)
    • Description: Returns the index of the first occurrence of the value 3.
index = my_list.index(3)
index
2
  • insert():
    • Syntax: my_list.insert(1, 7)
    • Description: Inserts the value 7 at index 1 in the list.
my_list.insert(1, 7)
my_list
[1, 7, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
  • pop():
    • Syntax: popped_value = my_list.pop()
    • Description: Removes and returns the last element from the list.
popped_value = my_list.pop()
popped_value
6
  • remove():
    • Syntax: my_list.remove(2)
    • Description: Removes the first occurrence of the value 2 from the list.
my_list.remove(2)
my_list
[1, 7, 3, 4, 5]
  • reverse():
    • Syntax: my_list.reverse()
    • Description: Reverses the order of elements in the list.
my_list.reverse()

my_list
[5, 4, 3, 7, 1]
  • sort():
    • Syntax: my_list.sort()
    • Description: Sorts the elements of the list in ascending order.
my_list.sort()
my_list
[1, 3, 4, 5, 7]

2.2 5.2 Dictionaries:

Dictionaries in Python are mutable collections of key-value pairs.

  • Create:
    • Syntax: my_dict = {"name": "John", "age": 25}
    • Description: Creates a dictionary with key-value pairs.
my_dict = {"name": "John", "age": 25}
my_dict
{'name': 'John', 'age': 25}
  • Access using for loop:

    • Syntax:

      for key, value in my_dict.items():
    print(key, value)

    • Description: Accesses key-value pairs using a for loop.

for key, value in my_dict.items():
    print(key, value)
name John
age 25
  • clear():
    • Syntax: my_dict.clear()
    • Description: Removes all items from the dictionary.
my_dict.clear()
my_dict
{}
  • copy():
    • Syntax: new_dict = my_dict.copy()
    • Description: Creates a shallow copy of the dictionary.
my_dict = {"name": "John", "age": 25}
new_dict = my_dict.copy()
new_dict
{'name': 'John', 'age': 25}
my_dict = {'name': 'John', 'age': 25, 'languages': ['Python', 'Java']}

shallow_copy = my_dict.copy()

my_dict['name'] = 'Java'
my_dict['languages'][0] = 'C++'

print(my_dict)
print(shallow_copy)
{'name': 'Java', 'age': 25, 'languages': ['C++', 'Java']}
{'name': 'John', 'age': 25, 'languages': ['C++', 'Java']}
from copy import deepcopy

new_dict = deepcopy(my_dict)
new_dict

my_dict['name'] = 'java'
print(my_dict)
print(new_dict)
{'name': 'java', 'age': 25, 'languages': ['C++', 'Java']}
{'name': 'Java', 'age': 25, 'languages': ['C++', 'Java']}
  • fromkeys():
    • Syntax: new_dict = dict.fromkeys(["name", "age"], "Unknown")
    • Description: Creates a new dictionary with specified keys and a default value.
new_dict = dict.fromkeys(["name", "age"], "Unknown")
new_dict
{'name': 'Unknown', 'age': 'Unknown'}
  • get():
    • Syntax: value = my_dict.get("name", "Not found")
    • Description: Gets the value for the specified key, or a default value if the key is not present.
value = my_dict.get("name", "Not found")
value
'java'
  • items():
    • Syntax: items = my_dict.items()
    • Description: Returns a view of key-value pairs in the dictionary.
items = my_dict.items()
items
dict_items([('name', 'java'), ('age', 25), ('languages', ['C++', 'Java'])])
  • keys():
    • Syntax: keys = my_dict.keys()
    • Description: Returns a view of keys in the dictionary.
keys = my_dict.keys()
keys
dict_keys(['name', 'age', 'languages'])
  • update():
    • Syntax: my_dict.update({"age": 26, "city": "New York"})
    • Description: Updates the dictionary with key-value pairs from another dictionary.
my_dict.update({"age": 26, "city": "New York"})
my_dict
{'name': 'java', 'age': 26, 'languages': ['C++', 'Java'], 'city': 'New York'}
  • values():
    • Syntax: values = my_dict.values()
    • Description: Returns a view of values in the dictionary.
values = my_dict.values()
values
dict_values(['java', 26, ['C++', 'Java'], 'New York'])

2.3 5.3 Sets:

Sets in Python are mutable, unordered collections of unique elements.

  • Declaring:
    • Syntax: my_set = {1, 2, 3}
    • Description: Declares a set with values 1, 2, and 3.
my_set = {1, 2, 3}
  • Accessing:
    • Sets do not support indexing or slicing.
my_set[0]
TypeError: 'set' object is not subscriptable
  • set():
    • Syntax: new_set = set([3, 4, 5])
    • Description: Creates a set from an iterable.
new_set = set([3, 4, 5])
new_set
{3, 4, 5}
  • frozenset():
    • Syntax: frozen_set = frozenset([1, 2, 3])
    • Description: Creates an immutable frozenset from an iterable.
frozen_set = frozenset([1, 2, 3])
frozen_set
frozenset({1, 2, 3})
  • issubset():
    • Syntax: is_subset = set1.issubset(set2)
    • Description: Checks if set1 is a subset of set2.
set1 = {1,2}
set2 = {1,2,3}
is_subset = set1.issubset(set2)
is_subset
True
  • issuperset():
    • Syntax: is_superset = set1.issuperset(set2)
    • Description: Checks if set1 is a superset of set2.
is_superset = set2.issuperset(set1)
is_superset
True
  • union():
    • Syntax: union_set = set1.union(set2)
    • Description: Returns the union of two sets.
union_set = set1.union(set2)
union_set
{1, 2, 3}
  • intersection():
    • Syntax: intersection_set = set1.intersection(set2)
    • Description: Returns the intersection of two sets.
intersection_set = set1.intersection(set2)
intersection_set
{1, 2}
  • difference():
    • Syntax: difference_set = set1.difference(set2)
    • Description: Returns the difference between two sets.
set1 = {1,2,3}
set2 = {3,4,5}
difference_set = set1.difference(set2)
difference_set
{1, 2}
set1 - set2
{1, 2}
  • symmetric_difference():
    • Syntax: symmetric_difference_set = set1.symmetric_difference(set2)
    • Description: Returns the symmetric difference between two sets.
symmetric_difference_set = set1.symmetric_difference(set2)
symmetric_difference_set
{1, 2, 4, 5}
  • copy():
    • Syntax: new_set = my_set.copy()
    • Description: Creates a shallow copy of the set.
new_set = my_set.copy()
new_set
{1, 2, 3}

2.4 5.4 Lambda functions:

Lambda functions are anonymous functions defined using the lambda keyword.

  • Map:
    • Syntax: mapped_values = map(lambda x: x * 2, [1, 2, 3])
    • Description: Applies the lambda function to each element of the iterable.
mapped_values = map(lambda x: x * 2, [1, 2, 3])
print(list(mapped_values))
[2, 4, 6]
  • Reduce:
    • Syntax: from functools import reduce; result = reduce(lambda x, y: x + y, [1, 2, 3])
    • Description: Applies the lambda function cumulatively to the elements of the iterable.
from functools import reduce
result = reduce(lambda x, y: x + y, [1, 2, 3])
result
6
  • Filter:
    • Syntax: filtered_values = filter(lambda x: x % 2 == 0, [1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
    • Description: Filters elements of the iterable based on the lambda function.
filtered_values = filter(lambda x: x % 2 == 0, [1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
print(list(filtered_values))
[2, 4]
